\begin_layout Itemize
Example of dyanmical system: 2 masses attached by a spring but if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{f}$
\end_inset

 (the fequency with which one mass moves) is 
\begin_inset Formula $\ll$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 (the resonant frequency of the spring) then it is debatable if the system
 is dynamical because the second mass just follows the motion of the first.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Optomechanical mechanical systems can slow light - see Oskar Painter's work
 ...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
i\hbar\partial_{t}\psi\left(x\right) & = & H\psi\left(x\right)+\left[\intop\left|\psi\left(x\right)\right|^{2}V_{G}\left(x,x^{'}\right)dx^{'}\right]\psi\left(x\right),\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

the second non-linear term is due to self-gravity (?) This theory is unitary
 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\intop\left|\psi\right|^{2}dx=1$
\end_inset

 always - it preserves norms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Stochastic gravity? 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\mu\nu}=8\pi\left\langle T_{\mu\nu}\right\rangle +\mbox{noise}$
\end_inset

 ? Can have like a classical stochastic process: 
\begin_inset Formula $8\pi\left\{ \hat{T}_{\mu\nu}-\left\langle \hat{T}_{\mu\nu}\right\rangle \right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Can also have a dissipative term on the RHS.
 Here we treat 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 as a classical field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
The moving (charged) mirror problem
\series default
: mirror moving with acceleration 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 or frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Photon pairs can be created.
 Frequency of photons: 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\gamma}\sim a/c$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
1/Q & = & \frac{1}{Q_{elastic}}+\frac{1}{Q_{casimir}}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

What should we use to detect this effect: cavity with a coil? (because we
 might have radial waves).
 Thing is 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega L/c\sim\left(2\pi10^{9}\right)\times\left(10\times10^{-9}\right)/3/10^{8}\sim10^{3}$
\end_inset

which results in very low frequency.
 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is how much the resonator moves ...
 so for reasonable frequencies we want 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 in the micrometer regime.
 Another solution is to try to add a signal (easier to detect side peaks):
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}\pm\omega_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Fluctuation dissipation theorem
\series default
 
\series bold
problem
\series default
: Optical spring ..
 
\begin_inset Formula $H=...+\hat{x}\hat{F}$
\end_inset

 where F is a field operator.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\hat{F}\left(t\right),\hat{F}\left(t^{'}\right)\right]\neq0$
\end_inset

, we have an optical spring because 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{x}^{\left(1\right)} & = & \hat{x}^{\left(0\right)}+\intop\left[x\left(t\right),x\left(t^{'}\right)\right]F^{\left(1\right)}\left(t^{'}\right)dt^{'}\\
\hat{F}^{\left(1\right)} & = & \hat{F}^{\left(0\right)}+\intop\left[F^{\left(0\right)}\left(t\right),F^{\left(0\right)}\left(t^{'}\right)\right]x^{\left(1\right)}\left(t^{'}\right)dt^{'}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}^{\left(0\right)}$
\end_inset

 is the zero point fluctuation of x.
 If 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\left[\hat{F}\left(t\right),\hat{F}\left(t^{'}\right)\right]=0$
\end_inset

 then we have no 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

